disease from
reaching Western bats, or so
scientists thought,

38:24.001 --> 38:26.237 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
until Huckabee's discovery.

38:26.270 --> 38:31.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some speculate that an infected
bat may have
hitched a ride on a freight
truck.

38:31.075 --> 38:36.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Others think hikers or cavers
may have unwittingly
carried the fungus on their
clothes or equipment.

38:36.814 --> 38:40.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since the first infected bat was
found in
the forests east of Seattle, the
white-nose

38:41.018 --> 38:45.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fungus has been found twice more
in Washington
state, both near the original
site around

38:46.023 --> 38:46.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
North Bend.

38:47.024 --> 38:51.996 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOMAN: We have bats in the net.

38:52.029 --> 38:57.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WERNER: Fear of a
white-nose outbreak
has jump-started research, not
just in Washington,

38:57.802 --> 39:01.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
but around the Northwest.

39:01.105 --> 39:05.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Central Oregon, ecologist Tom
Rodhouse
and a team of researchers are
collecting data

39:05.409 --> 39:06.777 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on local bats.

39:06.811 --> 39:08.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM RODHOUSE, National Park
Service: Bats
hang out in the dark.

39:08.279 --> 39:11.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They hang out in these big
cliffs and crevices
that we can't access.

39:11.215 --> 39:15.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we have gone for decades
without really
understanding what's happening
with bats.

39:15.986 --> 39:20.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WERNER: They're trying
to assess the
health and population size of
Oregon's 15

39:20.958 --> 39:22.693 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
species of bats.

39:22.727 --> 39:26.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM RODHOUSE: There's really no
way for us
to ascertain what's happening
with our bat

39:26.163 --> 39:31.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
populations without this kind of
a coordinated
large-scale survey effort.

39:32.002 --> 39:40.945 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL WERNER: Back in
Washington, researchers
such as Abby Tobin are trying to
learn how

39:40.978 --> 39:42.747 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
bats spend their winters.

39:42.780 --> 39:46.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABBY TOBIN, Researcher: We're
trying to figure
out what type of habitats
they're roosting

39:46.484 --> 39:51.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in, if they're hibernating
through the winter,
or if they are kind of active
throughout,

39:51.455 --> 39:57.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and also looking at those
habitats they're
using, and whether the
environment there is

39:57.061 --> 39:58.763 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conducive for the fungus to
thrive.

39:58.796 --> 40:10.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why don't we kind of go down a
little bit
and see away from the trail?

40:10.074 --> 40:18.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WERNER: She's setting up
bat detectors,
specialized microphones that can
pick up bats'

40:18.449 --> 40:20.351 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
high-frequency calls.

40:20.384 --> 40:26.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABBY TOBIN: Each bat has a
unique echolocation
call, and so we're able to
identify them based

40:26.657 --> 40:31.495 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on that call from those acoustic
detectors.

40:31.529 --> 40:38.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
From this, I could tell this is
canyon bat.

40:38.702 --> 40:44.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they have this typical kind
of hockey
stick shape look to their claw.

40:44.108 --> 40:51.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WERNER: In the lab,
Tobin looks for
small signs the disease is
taking hold in

40:51.749 --> 40:52.983 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Washington.

40:53.017 --> 40:56.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ABBY TOBIN: And there's a couple
little tiny
little holes.

40:56.153 --> 41:01.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I am looking right now to see if
there is
any damage to the wing
membranes, which would

41:01.725 --> 41:04.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be a sign that it had white-nose
syndrome.

41:04.895 --> 41:09.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's important to detect
white-nose syndrome
early because it allows us to
get a sense

41:09.433 --> 41:14.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of where it is, and so we might
be able to
do some sort of containment or
treatment with

41:14.104 --> 41:15.840 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the animals.

41:15.873 --> 41:20.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL WERNER: Despite
white-nose's deadly
effects on bats, it poses no
known threat

41:20.744 --> 41:21.879 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to people.

41:21.912 --> 41:23.981 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But many questions remain.

41:24.014 --> 41:28.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it could be years before
definitive answers
emerge.

41:28.352 --> 41:32.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Michael Werner
in Seattle.

41:32.523 --> 41:37.261 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And a postscript:
High school
students at our Student
Reporting Lab outside

41:37.294 --> 41:42.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of Louisville, Kentucky,
