41:59.783 --> 42:04.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's return to the war in
Syria, and focus
on the effect it is having on
children.

42:04.688 --> 42:07.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The schools have been
devastated.

42:07.057 --> 42:10.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
More than a third have closed
since the war
began.

42:10.661 --> 42:16.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a recent report by the
International Rescue
Committee found more than 1.7
million children

42:16.433 --> 42:19.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and youth are not attending
classes.

42:19.303 --> 42:22.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the focus of our weekly
segment Making
the Grade.

42:22.606 --> 42:26.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're joined by David
Miliband the president
of the International Rescue
Committee.

42:26.911 --> 42:31.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He recently visited the region
and refugee
children in Lebanon.

42:31.715 --> 42:34.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
David Miliband, welcome back to
the program.

42:34.151 --> 42:39.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know this war has taken a
terrible toll
on lives in so many ways, but
what is the

42:39.423 --> 42:43.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
main finding of your report on
the effect
on children and their ability to
learn?

42:43.360 --> 42:45.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND, President,
International Rescue
Committee: Thank you, Judy.

42:45.663 --> 42:50.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, the situation inside Syria
is obviously
top of the news because of the
crushing and

42:50.868 --> 42:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
appalling chemical weapons
attacks last week.

42:54.338 --> 43:00.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the long-term impact of six
years of war
on about 1.7 million children
inside the country

43:00.744 --> 43:04.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who are being denied education
is obviously
very grave indeed.

43:04.081 --> 43:09.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is the fundamental stress,
what is called
the toxic stress, of being
involved in a war.

43:09.386 --> 43:13.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And for those inside the
country, they're
denied the most basic access to
education.

43:13.190 --> 43:17.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, that problem is
doubled by the
experience of the refugees who
are out of

43:18.028 --> 43:22.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the country, 5.5 million
refugees out of the
country, half of them kids,
probably half

43:22.666 --> 43:24.468 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of those not getting an
education at all.

43:24.501 --> 43:29.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it is true to talk about a
generation
of Syrian schoolchildren being
denied the

43:29.206 --> 43:31.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
most basic elements of an
education.

43:31.241 --> 43:36.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, that stands in
stark contrast
to the fact that they would have
expected,

43:36.513 --> 43:41.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a middle-income country,
which Syria was
before 2011, to get a decent
education.

43:41.151 --> 43:43.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What does this
mean?

43:43.053 --> 43:47.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Based on this report that the
International
Rescue Committee has put
together, what does

43:47.391 --> 43:52.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this mean specifically in terms
of children's
literacy, their ability to read,
their ability

43:52.162 --> 43:53.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to do basic math?

43:54.031 --> 44:00.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, we found
that children
in grades six, seven, eight, so
children almost

44:00.671 --> 44:06.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
approaching teenage years, were
unable to
do the kind of sums or spelling
that you would

44:06.543 --> 44:08.312 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
expect from a grade one student.

44:08.345 --> 44:14.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's what six years of
education being
lost means, never mind the huge
blow to the

44:14.451 --> 44:19.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
children's understanding and
self-esteem that
comes from seeing their country
blown apart,

44:19.156 --> 44:22.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and often their families blown
apart as well.

44:22.359 --> 44:27.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think that the message
I would get
across to your viewers is that
the toll on

44:27.297 --> 44:30.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
children is almost greater than
on any other
group.

44:30.134 --> 44:34.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, secondly, never
underestimate the resilience
of the children and the ability
of them, when

44:34.972 --> 44:38.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
given proper educational
provision, to bounce
back.

44:38.475 --> 44:42.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We, the International Rescue
Committee, offer
education in the north of Syria
to children

44:42.713 --> 44:43.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
inside the country.

44:43.847 --> 44:46.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also offer education in the
neighboring
states.

44:46.350 --> 44:51.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we find is that,
however hard the
children have been hit, there's
a remarkable

44:51.221 --> 44:53.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
capacity to bounce back, if
they're given
proper help.

44:53.657 --> 44:57.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that makes international
humanitarian
aid especially important.

44:57.094 --> 44:59.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what is
proper help?

44:59.096 --> 45:00.831 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What does that consist of?

45:00.864 --> 45:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And what can be done about this?

45:02.666 --> 45:07.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because people are certainly
looking for ways
out of this war, but, if
anything, that looks

45:07.204 --> 45:09.006 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
harder than ever today.

45:09.039 --> 45:14.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: You're right
about the huge
diplomatic effort that's going
to be necessary.

45:14.111 --> 45:18.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, on the humanitarian front,
and especially
the educational front, there are
two things

45:18.582 --> 45:20.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that are essential.

45:20.384 --> 45:22.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, there's no point
in pretending
that kids who have been through
a war are

45:23.020 --> 45:26.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
like any other first grader or
fifth grader
turning up for school.

45:26.657 --> 45:30.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They need proper attention to
their social
and emotional resources.

45:30.994 --> 45:35.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's called the toxic stress
that they have
suffered is effectively brain
damage and/or

45:35.566 --> 45:38.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what would be called amongst
adults PTSD.

45:38.235 --> 45:41.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And these children need to have
that addressed
before they're able to access
learning.

45:41.605 --> 45:46.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, in addition to those
social and emotional
skills and resources that they
need to build

45:46.276 --> 45:49.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up, they also need the basic
elements of an
education.

45:50.013 --> 45:55.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And our argument is that, at a
time when the
overall humanitarian budget is
under huge

45:55.586 --> 46:00.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stress, at a time when less than
2 percent
of the global humanitarian
budget is spent

46:00.491 --> 46:05.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on education, that is the worst
possible time
for the administration in
Washington to be

46:05.996 --> 46:11.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
talking about one-third cuts, 31
percent cuts
in America's contribution to
humanitarian

46:11.268 --> 46:15.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
aid, because America has often
marked itself
out for its commitment on the
humanitarian

46:15.739 --> 46:17.174 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
front.

46:17.207 --> 46:19.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And those children in Syria who
we surveyed,
they need America's help.

46:19.610 --> 46:23.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you're saying
there's a
direct link between what the
U.S. does in

46:23.213 --> 46:29.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terms of foreign aid and the
long-term repercussions,
survival of these children, and
their ability

46:29.486 --> 46:32.523 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to be functioning human beings?

46:32.556 --> 46:35.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, you don't
need to just
take my word for it.

46:35.592 --> 46:39.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I lead a humanitarian
organization, so you
might expect me to say that
humanitarian aid

46:39.696 --> 46:41.064 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is important.

46:41.098 --> 46:43.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But just listen to the U.S.
defense secretary,
Secretary Mattis.

46:43.934 --> 46:48.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's very clear, as a military
man, that military
effort on its own, it needs to
be -- is not

46:48.505 --> 46:50.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
enough on its own.

46:50.374 --> 46:54.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It needs to be allied obviously
to diplomatic
effort, but also to humanitarian
and development

46:54.344 --> 46:56.113 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
efforts as well.

46:56.146 --> 46:59.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those three aspects of
American foreign
policy, the military, the
diplomacy and the

46:59.817 --> 47:02.686 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
humanitarian development, need
to go together.

47:02.719 --> 47:09.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the suggestion from the
administration
that now is the time to slash
America's leadership

47:09.426 --> 47:11.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on humanitarian aid seems
extremely misguided.

47:11.962 --> 47:16.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're living through the world's
-- certainly
this century's worst civil war
in Syria.

47:16.800 --> 47:20.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know there are four famines
that are hitting
parts of Africa.

47:20.871 --> 47:23.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The global refugee crisis is at
its height.

47:23.874 --> 47:27.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Humanitarian aid is an essential
commitment
to the future of those children,
but it's

47:27.811 --> 47:30.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
also a stabilizer of the
societies from which
they come.

47:30.280 --> 47:32.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, you
mentioned the defense
secretary, James Mattis.

47:32.883 --> 47:37.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, he said at his news
conference today
that the U.S. -- it sounded as
if what he

47:37.654 --> 47:42.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was saying was that, unless
there is another
chemical weapons attack by the
Assad regime,

47:42.526 --> 47:47.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at this point, the U.S. has no
further plan
to intervene militarily.

47:47.197 --> 47:50.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What does that mean for the
efforts of groups
like the International Rescue
Committee?

47:50.701 --> 47:56.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, we can
report from the
ground that our staff -- I have
got about

47:56.540 --> 48:01.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
1,400 staff working for the
International
Rescue Committee inside Syria.

48:01.178 --> 48:04.248 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They rushed towards that
chemical weapons
attack in an ambulance.

48:04.281 --> 48:09.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They rescued 10 people, took
them to a hospital
in Idlib, and saved their lives.

48:09.519 --> 48:13.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, obviously, they are in fear
not just
of chemical weapons attacks, but
conventional

48:13.557 --> 48:15.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
weapons attacks as well.

48:15.392 --> 48:20.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so my message from the
ground would be
that we -- it's incumbent on
American political

48:20.998 --> 48:26.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
leadership to make stop the
killing the central
demand that is made of all the
actors in the

48:26.603 --> 48:28.372 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
conflict.

48:28.405 --> 48:32.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Until we stop the killing, then
not only will
the humanitarian situation get
worse, but

48:32.142 --> 48:36.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the prospects for any kind of
durable peace
evaporate as well.

48:36.613 --> 48:41.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my fear from the ground is
that, in the
few days since the chemical
weapons attacks,

48:41.785 --> 48:47.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there's actually been an
intensification of
the conventional weapons
warfare.

48:47.057 --> 48:51.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's obviously cold
comfort to anyone
on the ground trying to live
their life inside

48:51.495 --> 48:53.397 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Syria.

48:53.430 --> 48:56.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But it was clear
today, again,
just quickly, in listening to
Secretary Mattis,

48:56.300 --> 49:00.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the administration is right
now drawing
a line between responding if
there is a chemical

49:00.804 --> 49:06.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
weapons attack, but something
very different
if it's short of, even if it's
barrel bombs

49:06.710 --> 49:08.478 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on civilians.

49:08.512 --> 49:12.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, obviously,
as a leader
of a humanitarian organization,
it's not for

49:12.049 --> 49:15.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
me to advocate one military
tactic or another.

49:15.319 --> 49:20.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I can say is that the
situation on the
ground is grave and getting
worse, that the

49:20.657 --> 49:26.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cease-fires that are being
proclaimed at various
points haven't held at all, and
that, with

49:26.430 --> 49:34.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
500,000 dead, 5.5 million
refugees, it's well
past the time when Syria wasn't
just a humanitarian

49:34.538 --> 49:36.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
emergency, but it was a
political emergency
as well.

49:36.940 --> 49:41.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's a source of massive
instability across
the Middle East and into Europe.

49:41.578 --> 49:44.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that calls for the highest
levels of diplomatic
and political engagement.

49:44.614 --> 49:48.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David Miliband,
the president
of the International Rescue
Committee, thank

49:48.418 --> 49:49.386 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

49:49.419 --> 49:55.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Thank you so
much.

49:55.258 --> 50:04.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
A museum exhibition
explores a different way of
covering the news

50:04.801 --> 50:06.336 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
through art.

50:06.370 --> 50:09.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown is back with the
story from
a recent trip to Los Angeles.

50:09.806 --> 50:17.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Twenty-four-hour
news channels,
digital news feeds, the latest
tweet, it's

50:17.247 --> 50:23.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the now-familiar, nonstop,
sometimes overwhelming
world of news and information we
live in.

50:23.620 --> 50:28.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But that sense of news
bombardment isn't really
new, and an exhibition at the
Getty Museum

50:28.959 --> 50:34.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Los Angeles shows how artists
have often
commented on, wrestled and
played with it.

50:34.931 --> 50:36.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Curator Arpad Kovacs:

50:36.800 --> 50:38.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARPAD KOVACS, Curator, J. Paul
Getty Museum:
Most of us just don't know how
to make sense

50:38.735 --> 50:40.470 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of it.

50:40.504 --> 50:44.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's where artists
step in and
are able to kind of make
something fruitful

50:44.608 --> 50:50.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and sort of thoughtful, and take
the images,
take the text, take the
information as source

50:50.814 --> 50:56.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
material to make something that
looks critically
at the information that we
receive every single

50:56.286 --> 50:58.121 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
day.

50:58.155 --> 51:01.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The exhibition,
titled Breaking
News, takes us to a pre-Internet
era, featuring

51:01.758 --> 51:07.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
work by artists often seeking
political, as
well as aesthetic expression.

51:07.064 --> 51:12.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For Martha Rosler, the starting
point was
"LIFE" magazine as a guide to
the American

51:12.269 --> 51:13.737 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
psyche.

51:13.770 --> 51:17.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As the Vietnam War raged, the
magazine captured
the war in photographs.

51:17.974 --> 51:20.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But turn the page to sumptuous
home interiors.

51:20.944 --> 51:26.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rosler put the two together, in
one photo,
Pat Nixon in the White House,
with the image

51:26.983 --> 51:29.052 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of a war victim over the
fireplace.

51:29.086 --> 51:34.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARPAD KOVACS: She's making this
juxtaposition,
bringing these two disparate
images together,

51:34.424 --> 51:42.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in an effort to show how we can
sometimes
be oblivious to what's happening
in this world.

51:42.232 --> 51:44.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD BLUMBERG, Artist: This
stuff is from
'70-'72.

51:44.234 --> 51:50.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Artist Donald
Blumberg also
sought to transform a news
medium into a work

51:50.073 --> 51:53.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of art, one that says something
about the
times.

51:53.944 --> 51:58.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He took images from newspaper
stories about
slain soldiers or war
atrocities.

51:58.648 --> 52:06.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DONALD BLUMBERG: And I
re-photographed them,
and I wanted to enlarge them to
a size that

52:06.556 --> 52:10.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was inescapable for the viewer
to pass.

52:10.560 --> 52:14.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was intended to be a
direct political
act against the war in Vietnam.

52:14.798 --> 52:16.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's what it was intended to
do.

52:16.366 --> 52:19.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: By saying, look
hard at these
photographs that sort of appear.

52:19.603 --> 52:20.570 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DONALD BLUMBERG: Look hard.

52:20.604 --> 52:22.339 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You can't escape it.

52:22.372 --> 52:25.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He also began
photographing
his television set, freezing in
time major

52:25.742 --> 52:27.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
historical events.

52:27.744 --> 52:32.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His first work captured images
from the funeral
of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

52:32.315 --> 52:39.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD BLUMBERG: It was a way of
creating
a reportage to photograph off
the television

52:39.723 --> 52:46.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and translate it into a mosaic,
a mosaic in
which a person could look at the
whole story

52:46.963 --> 52:56.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and break it up into little
fragments, one
cell, two cell, horizontally,
diagonally.

52:56.139 --> 53:03.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Then there's a
kind of strange
news poem created by Omer Fast
in the wake

53:03.346 --> 53:05.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the 9/11 attacks.

53:05.615 --> 53:09.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He took single words spoken by
CNN anchors
and reporters.

53:09.519 --> 53:11.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You will certainly recognize one
of them.

53:11.421 --> 53:12.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The standard of
reporting.

53:12.756 --> 53:16.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: To fashion a
piece about fear
and anxiety.

53:16.960 --> 53:21.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Robert Heinecken played with
news anchors
in a different way, as a kind of
commodity,

53:21.798 --> 53:26.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in his piece, Case Study in
Finding An Appropriate
Newswoman.

53:26.403 --> 53:30.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He used photos of newscasters
and combined
them into an idealized
co-anchor.

53:30.874 --> 53:37.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARPAD KOVACS: I think what he
was interested
in is trying to reveal all of
the complex

53:37.714 --> 53:44.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decisions that go into making
such a choice
that the general public is not
aware of.

53:44.521 --> 53:51.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here, we have five panels in
which he's reproduced
issues of "LIFE" magazine.

53:51.161 --> 53:56.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For some artists,
the subject
was what's left out, what's not
there.

53:56.866 --> 54:03.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chilean artist Alfredo Jaar
created this large-scale
five-panel piece with every
cover of "LIFE"

54:03.707 --> 54:04.674 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
magazine.

54:04.708 --> 54:06.243 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
In a kind of "Where's Waldo?"

54:06.276 --> 54:09.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
style, he called it Searching
for Africa in
Life.

54:09.446 --> 54:14.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARPAD KOVACS: When you look at
this work,
you realize that there are very
few instances

54:14.784 --> 54:17.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where the continent of Africa is
represented.

54:17.921 --> 54:23.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in many of those instances,
it's actually
rather ambiguous whether the
cover pertains

54:23.526 --> 54:26.630 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to a story that deals with
Africa.

54:26.663 --> 54:30.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The news as art,
the art of
the news.

54:30.267 --> 54:34.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The exhibition Breaking News is
at the Getty
through April.

